## Description {#details}

<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/function">Function</a> information in GSYM files encodes information for one contiguous address range.

If a function has discontiguous address ranges, they will need to be encoded using multiple <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> objects.

ENCODING

The function information gets the function start address as an argument to the FunctionInfo::decode(...) function. This information is calculated from the GSYM header and an address offset from the GSYM address offsets table. The encoded <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> information must be aligned to a 4 byte boundary.

The encoded data for a <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> starts with fixed data that all function info objects have:

ENCODING NAME DESCRIPTION ========= =========== ==================================================== uint32&#95;t Size The size in bytes of this function. uint32&#95;t Name The string table offset of the function name.

The optional data in a <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> object follows this fixed information and consists of a stream of tuples that consist of:

ENCODING NAME DESCRIPTION ========= =========== ==================================================== uint32&#95;t <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/debuginfo/lib/debuginfo/gsym/functioninfo-cpp/#a3e1eb307ada3e1ef3a115f4c734aa5ee">InfoType</a> An &quot;InfoType&quot; enumeration that describes the type of optional data that is encoded. uint32&#95;t InfoLength The size in bytes of the encoded data that immediately follows this length if this value is greater than zero. uint8&#95;t&#91;&#93; InfoData Encoded bytes that represent the data for the &quot;InfoType&quot;. These bytes are only present if &quot;InfoLength&quot; is greater than zero.

The &quot;InfoType&quot; is an enumeration:

enum <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/debuginfo/lib/debuginfo/gsym/functioninfo-cpp/#a3e1eb307ada3e1ef3a115f4c734aa5ee">InfoType</a> &#123; EndOfList = 0u, LineTableInfo = 1u, <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/inlineinfo">InlineInfo</a> = 2u, <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/mergedfunctionsinfo">MergedFunctionsInfo</a> = 3u, <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/callsiteinfo">CallSiteInfo</a> = 4u &#125;;

This stream of tuples is terminated by a &quot;InfoType&quot; whose value is InfoType::EndOfList and a zero for &quot;InfoLength&quot;. This signifies the end of the optional information list. This format allows us to add new optional information data to a <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> object over time and allows older clients to still parse the format and skip over any data that they don&#39;t understand or want to parse.

So the function information encoding essentially looks like:

struct &#123; uint32&#95;t Size; uint32&#95;t Name; struct &#123; uint32&#95;t <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/debuginfo/lib/debuginfo/gsym/functioninfo-cpp/#a3e1eb307ada3e1ef3a115f4c734aa5ee">InfoType</a>; uint32&#95;t InfoLength; uint8&#95;t InfoData&#91;InfoLength&#93;; &#125;&#91;N&#93;; &#125;

Where &quot;N&quot; is the number of tuples.

## Public Member Functions

### cacheEncoding() {#a9542e71642930ba15c6f0f7788d8c654}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>uint64&#95;t FunctionInfo::cacheEncoding ()</>}>
Encode this function info into the internal byte cache and return the size in bytes.

When segmenting GSYM files we need to know how big each <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> will encode into so we can generate segments of the right size. We don&#39;t want to have to encode a <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> twice, so we can cache the encoded bytes and re-use then when calling FunctionInfo::encode(...).


<SectionUser title="Returns">
The size in bytes of the <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> if it were to be encoded into a byte stream.
</SectionUser>

Declaration at line <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/debuginfo/include/llvm/debuginfo/gsym/functioninfo-h/#l00170">170</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/debuginfo/include/llvm/debuginfo/gsym/functioninfo-h">FunctionInfo.h</a>, definition at line <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/debuginfo/lib/debuginfo/gsym/functioninfo-cpp/#l00119">119</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/debuginfo/lib/debuginfo/gsym/functioninfo-cpp">FunctionInfo.cpp</a>.
</MemberDefinition>

### encode() {#ab6deec968e0067bd7e7cd91892043097}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>llvm::Expected&lt; uint64&#95;t &gt; FunctionInfo::encode (<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/gsym/filewriter">FileWriter</a> &amp; O, bool NoPadding=false) const</>}>
Encode this object into <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/gsym/filewriter">FileWriter</a> stream.

<ParametersList title="Parameters">
<ParametersListItem name="O">The binary stream to write the data to at the current file position.</ParametersListItem>
<ParametersListItem name="NoPadding">Directly write the <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> data, without any padding By default, <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> will be 4-byte aligned by padding with 0&#39;s at the start. This is OK since the function will return the offset of actual data in the stream. However when writing <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a>&#39;s as a stream, the padding will break the decoding of the data - since the offset where the <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> starts is not kept in this scenario.</ParametersListItem>
</ParametersList>

<SectionUser title="Returns">
An error object that indicates failure or the offset of the function info that was successfully written into the stream.
</SectionUser>

Declaration at line <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/debuginfo/include/llvm/debuginfo/gsym/functioninfo-h/#l00158">158</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/debuginfo/include/llvm/debuginfo/gsym/functioninfo-h">FunctionInfo.h</a>, definition at line <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/debuginfo/lib/debuginfo/gsym/functioninfo-cpp/#l00134">134</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/debuginfo/lib/debuginfo/gsym/functioninfo-cpp">FunctionInfo.cpp</a>.

Query if a <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> has rich debug info.

<SectionUser title="Returns">
A bool that indicates if this object has something else than range and name. When converting information from a symbol table and from debug info, we might end up with multiple <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> objects for the same range and we need to be able to tell which one is the better object to use.

### isValid() {#a43805f0959f25f9637f816f36fe806f1}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype="bool llvm::gsym::FunctionInfo::isValid () const"
  labels = {["inline"]}>
Query if a <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> object is valid.

Address and size can be zero and there can be no line entries for a symbol so the only indication this entry is valid is if the name is not zero. This can happen when extracting information from symbol tables that do not encode symbol sizes. In that case only the address and name will be filled in.


<SectionUser title="Returns">
A boolean indicating if this <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> is valid.
</SectionUser>

  prototype={<>llvm::Expected&lt; LookupResult &gt; FunctionInfo::lookup (<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/dataextractor">DataExtractor</a> &amp; Data, <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/target/lib/target/aarch64/aarch64promoteconstant-cpp/#a90f8350fecae261c25be85d38b451bff">const</a> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/gsym/gsymreader">GsymReader</a> &amp; GR, uint64&#95;t FuncAddr, uint64&#95;t Addr, std::optional&lt; <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/dataextractor">DataExtractor</a> &gt; &#42; MergedFuncsData=nullptr)</>}
  labels = {["static"]}>
Lookup an address within a <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> object&#39;s data stream.

Instead of decoding an entire <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> object when doing lookups, we can decode only the information we need from the <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a>&#39;s data for the specific address. The lookup result information is returned as a <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/lookupresult">LookupResult</a>.


<ParametersList title="Parameters">
<ParametersListItem name="Data">The binary stream to read the data from. This object must have the data for the object starting at offset zero. The data can contain more data than needed.</ParametersListItem>
<ParametersListItem name="GR">The GSYM reader that contains the string and file table that will be used to fill in information in the returned result.</ParametersListItem>
<ParametersListItem name="FuncAddr">The function start address decoded from the <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/gsym/gsymreader">GsymReader</a>.</ParametersListItem>
<ParametersListItem name="Addr">The address to lookup.</ParametersListItem>
<ParametersListItem name="MergedFuncsData">A pointer to an optional <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/dataextractor">DataExtractor</a> that, if non-null, will be set to the raw data of the MergedFunctionInfo, if present.</ParametersListItem>
</ParametersList>

<SectionUser title="Returns">
An <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/lookupresult">LookupResult</a> or an error describing the issue that was encountered during decoding. An error should only be returned if the address is not contained in the <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/gsym/functioninfo">FunctionInfo</a> or if the data is corrupted.
</SectionUser>
